{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"919bf9d9-4505-43ee-abda-adc2c864fdff","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check under **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — If enabled (`ulimit -c unlimited` before running), they land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — You can also search the unified log:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourAppName\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash reports include the faulting thread's stack trace, signal info, and loaded images — often enough to diagnose the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"69dfc2bd-16ea-43e7-b74f-984c1a9b6517","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":284,"requestId":"6803:247AEF:2CD9DC9:3195662:69FD41DA"},"id":"0b1e0def-f5df-42d8-90fc-0d1789878ea1","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:52:36.011Z","parentId":"92af41c6-6fd6-45c8-a51f-8e7f4469055b"}
